---
// Layout placeholder shown between "auth passed" and "first SSE frame
// arrived". Sits inside the table body (#systems-body) so it collapses
// cleanly once the real rows are rendered.
//
// Design rationale (matches the minimalist theme):
//
//   * The auth gate (index.astro / admin.astro) already shows a
//     "Checking access..." spinner while the browser verifies the
//     privacy config. Once auth passes, the SSE channel typically
//     delivers the first full snapshot within ~100–300 ms.
//
//   * The placeholder below is a **row-preview skeleton**: five
//     miniature "dot + bar" pairs that echo the real table's left-column
//     shape (status dot + service name). This gives the user a subtle
//     hint that rows are about to fill this area, without copying the
//     full column grid (which would re-introduce the width-jump bug —
//     the previous skeleton referenced --first-col-width, so when that
//     variable was recomputed on data arrival the whole skeleton would
//     snap sideways).
//
//   * Width behaviour:
//       - Desktop (≥1024 px): the wrapper uses flex +
//         `justify-content: center`, so the preview sits in the middle
//         of the card and looks balanced and intentional on the wide
//         layout.
//       - Mobile / tablet (<1024 px): the table uses `min-w-[1000px]`
//         with horizontal scroll, so centering inside that 1000 px box
//         would push the preview to ~500 px — off-screen on a 375 px
//         phone. A media query switches `justify-content` to
//         `flex-start` so mobile users see the feedback at the
//         left-edge of the visible viewport without having to scroll.
//
//   * Timing:
//       - The preview fades in 160 ms after mount. When SSE is fast
//         (the common case) the whole container is hidden before that
//         delay elapses, so nothing flashes in.
//       - Once visible, each dot/bar pair breathes at 0.28 → 0.62
//         opacity on a 1.8 s cycle, staggered by 180 ms so the motion
//         reads as a calm wave rather than a synchronous throb.
//
//   * When real data lands, SystemTable flips this container to
//     display:none AFTER it has applied the final column width and
//     waited one animation frame, so there is never a moment where the
//     user sees columns moving. Only the row-level `data-row-in`
//     keyframe plays, entirely at the settled width.
//
//   * Accessibility: the wrapper carries `role="status"` (implicit
//     aria-live: polite) so that when SystemTable's loadData() catch
//     branch swaps the pulse out for an error message like "Failed to
//     connect to backend…", assistive tech announces it. The inner
//     `.loading-pulse` carries `aria-hidden="true"` because the
//     dot/bar shapes are purely decorative — they should not be
//     described as "dot, bar, dot, bar, …" to screen-reader users.
---

<div id="loading-indicator" role="status">
  <div class="loading-pulse" aria-hidden="true">
    <div class="pulse-row pulse-row-a">
      <span class="pulse-dot"></span>
      <span class="pulse-bar"></span>
    </div>
    <div class="pulse-row pulse-row-b">
      <span class="pulse-dot"></span>
      <span class="pulse-bar"></span>
    </div>
    <div class="pulse-row pulse-row-c">
      <span class="pulse-dot"></span>
      <span class="pulse-bar"></span>
    </div>
    <div class="pulse-row pulse-row-d">
      <span class="pulse-dot"></span>
      <span class="pulse-bar"></span>
    </div>
    <div class="pulse-row pulse-row-e">
      <span class="pulse-dot"></span>
      <span class="pulse-bar"></span>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<style>
  /* Wrapper — reserves a natural amount of vertical space. The table
     header (SystemTableHeaderRow) is rendered as `display: none`
     during the pulse phase so it contributes zero height; the
     loading block therefore sits flush against the table card's top
     border and this min-height alone defines the area the user sees
     pulsing. 200 px is tall enough for the five-row preview + its
     vertical padding to feel substantial, and slightly shorter than
     a typical populated table so that when real rows land the table
     only grows downward (never jumps up), matching the dashboard's
     "content arrives from above" feel.
     `justify-content: center` centres the preview inside the card on
     desktop; `align-items: center` keeps it vertically centred within
     the reserved height. As a bonus, when loadingIndicator.innerHTML
     is replaced with an error message (see loadData() catch branch
     in SystemTable.astro), that message is automatically centred in
     both axes. */
  #loading-indicator {
    min-height: 200px;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
  }

  /* On viewports where the table's `min-w-[1000px]` forces a horizontal
     scrollbar (phones, narrow tablets), the scroll container is wider
     than the viewport, so centring the preview inside it parks the
     content at ~500 px — off-screen on a 375 px phone. Falling back to
     `flex-start` left-aligns the preview so mobile users see the
     feedback immediately without scrolling sideways. The 1023 px
     threshold matches Tailwind's `lg:` breakpoint, which is where the
     1000 px min-width starts to overflow typical handheld viewports. */
  @media (max-width: 1023px) {
    #loading-indicator {
      justify-content: flex-start;
    }
  }

  /* Preview container. max-width caps the bar lengths so they don't
     stretch awkwardly on very wide cards; padding gives the dots/bars
     breathing room from the table's inner edges. Horizontal alignment
     is delegated to the flex container above so we don't need a second
     margin:auto here. */
  .loading-pulse {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 16px;
    width: 100%;
    max-width: 520px;
    padding: 28px 24px;
    opacity: 0;
    animation: pulse-appear 280ms 160ms cubic-bezier(0.16, 1, 0.3, 1) forwards;
  }

  /* Each row groups a status-dot placeholder and a bar placeholder,
     mirroring the real table's first column (status dot + service
     name). They breathe as a pair so the pulsing reads as a row
     blinking, not as independent elements. */
  .pulse-row {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 10px;
    animation: pulse-breathe 1.8s ease-in-out infinite;
    will-change: opacity;
  }

  .pulse-dot {
    flex-shrink: 0;
    width: 8px;
    height: 8px;
    border-radius: 999px;
    background: #333333;
  }

  .pulse-bar {
    height: 12px;
    border-radius: 999px;
    background: #282828;
  }

  /* Light-theme palette — slightly lighter neutrals that still read as
     "placeholder" against the near-white card background. */
  :global(html.light) .pulse-dot {
    background: #d4d4d4;
  }

  :global(html.light) .pulse-bar {
    background: #e5e5e5;
  }

  /* Bar widths are intentionally varied to echo the organic variation
     of real server names (some short, some long), so the preview reads
     as a list of items rather than five identical bars. */
  .pulse-row-a .pulse-bar { width: 62%; }
  .pulse-row-b .pulse-bar { width: 84%; }
  .pulse-row-c .pulse-bar { width: 46%; }
  .pulse-row-d .pulse-bar { width: 72%; }
  .pulse-row-e .pulse-bar { width: 38%; }

  /* Stagger the breathing so the rows pulse as a gentle wave top→bottom
     rather than all throbbing in sync, which would look mechanical. */
  .pulse-row-a { animation-delay:   0ms; }
  .pulse-row-b { animation-delay: 180ms; }
  .pulse-row-c { animation-delay: 360ms; }
  .pulse-row-d { animation-delay: 540ms; }
  .pulse-row-e { animation-delay: 720ms; }

  @keyframes pulse-breathe {
    0%, 100% { opacity: 0.28; }
    50%      { opacity: 0.62; }
  }

  @keyframes pulse-appear {
    from { opacity: 0; }
    to   { opacity: 1; }
  }

  @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
    .loading-pulse {
      animation: none;
      opacity: 1;
    }
    .pulse-row {
      animation: none;
      opacity: 0.42;
    }
  }
</style>
